The National Trust is mentioned on the secret life of bats
New research being carried out on land in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape when searching for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of single flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common pipistrelles and soprano as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
An expert analysis of the sounds of all recordings will ascertain the frequency of bat calls and what species are doing what.
A habitat map and a report will then be produced that will create a detailed picture of their behavioural landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of pastures and how best to maintain woodlands for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and around the UK has declined considerably over the past century.
They are under threat from construction and development work affecting nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can poison papers to trap insects and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
The bats are not actually blind.
However, because of their notoriety hunting traditions their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated ecolocality technique to indicate insects and obstacles in their path when flying.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave land in Dumfries and Galloway, welcoming eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave we have a very good area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, many veteran trees and all the good habitat.
But there is much more about bats that is not yet known, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive."
It stresses the importance of checking bats for maintenance in properties as it is possible that unintentional destruction of a single maternity nest can kill up to 400 women and young, possibly destroying an entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass or harass them or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer for the Night Butterfly Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we still don't know how their populations are going."
